                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3g15tx51/manifest/annotation/p4",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>6</p>\n            <p>Resolved That the will of the majority is the fundamental<lb/> law of all\n                societies—civil political &amp; Religious—</p>\n            <p>Resolved That the Trustees were elected under<lb/> the implied assurance they would\n                recognize this right</p>\n            <p>Resolved that sufficient presumptive evidence<lb/> has been given to show that 4 out\n                of the 7 of the<lb/> Trustees—(I will give their names <persName>Abm.\n                    Tobias</persName>\n                <persName>Sol Moses</persName><lb/>\n                <persName>Isaiah Moses</persName> &amp; <persName>Isaac Woolf</persName>) wish to\n                elect a<lb/> body of men termed seceeders whose aim is to break<lb/> down the\n                service now established &amp; to turn out<lb/> the Hazan, thus making a majority\n                yield to<lb/> the wishes of a minority.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\"><persName>Mr Cordoza</persName> endeavoured to sustain<lb/> these\n                Resolutions with real <hi rend=\"underline\">federal</hi> sophistry—<lb/>\n                <persName>Mr. Tobias</persName> answered him very ably and told<lb/> him they were\n                unconstitutional.</p>\n            <p>The last Resolution suspended the power<lb/> of the Trustees &amp; placed the\n                government in<lb/> the hands of the Prest &amp; 5 men selected<lb/> by him. It was\n                here <persName>Mr Tobias</persName> noticed<lb/> its unconstitutionality and told\n                him that<lb/> the meeting was not called for to alter the<lb/> constitution, to be\n                so, the Petition should come<lb/> before the Trustees. This was argued at<lb/> great\n                length, some avowing their determination<lb/> to trample on the constitution, &amp;\n                return to<lb/>\n                <sic>arnachy</sic> &amp; <hi rend=\"underline\">nullification</hi>.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3g15tx51/canvas/p4"
                }
              ]
            }
